00:00:17,818 --> 00:00:21,058
TIM COOK:
Good morning!

2
00:00:21,054 --> 00:00:23,294
Good morning!

3
00:00:23,290 --> 00:00:23,860
Good morning.

4
00:00:23,857 --> 00:00:27,727
Good morning.

5
00:00:30,731 --> 00:00:31,431
Good morning!

6
00:00:31,431 --> 00:00:35,871
Thanks for joining us.

7
00:00:35,869 --> 00:00:37,539
And welcome to San Francisco.

8
00:00:37,537 --> 00:00:41,537
Welcome to WWDC 2015.

9
00:00:41,541 --> 00:00:44,611
Although we may not
have any -- thank you --

10
00:00:44,611 --> 00:00:48,411
high-flying trapeze acts, we
do have a lot of great things

11
00:00:48,415 --> 00:00:50,415
to talk about this morning.

12
00:00:50,417 --> 00:00:53,757
This developer conference
continues to be the epicenter

13
00:00:53,754 --> 00:00:58,824
of change for not only
Apple, but the industry.

14
00:00:58,825 --> 00:01:02,195
This is our 26th WWDC.

15
00:01:02,195 --> 00:01:05,795
We have attendees today
from over 70 countries,

16
00:01:05,799 --> 00:01:09,369
and 80 percent are here
for the very first time.

17
00:01:09,369 --> 00:01:14,909
[Applause]

18
00:01:14,908 --> 00:01:19,148
This is our most
global conference ever.

19
00:01:19,146 --> 00:01:24,386
And a special shout-out for
our 350 scholarship winners.

20
00:01:24,384 --> 00:01:31,854
[Cheers and applause]

21
00:01:31,858 --> 00:01:33,828
These guys are unbelievable.

22
00:01:33,827 --> 00:01:35,427
I spent some time
with them yesterday.

23
00:01:35,429 --> 00:01:39,299
Our youngest scholarship
winner is a 12-year-old girl

24
00:01:39,299 --> 00:01:40,439
from New York.

25
00:01:40,434 --> 00:01:43,904
She is going to have a
fantastic future ahead.

26
00:01:43,904 --> 00:01:45,904
[Applause]

27
00:01:45,906 --> 00:01:48,406
We've got over a hundred
sessions planned for you

28
00:01:48,408 --> 00:01:51,408
and over 150 labs so that
you can get your hands

29
00:01:51,411 --> 00:01:54,051
on our latest technologies.

30
00:01:54,047 --> 00:01:57,617
And we've got over a thousand
Apple engineers to answer just

31
00:01:57,617 --> 00:02:00,717
about any question
that you might have.

32
00:02:00,721 --> 00:02:02,591
Now, we've got a lot more
people that would have liked

33
00:02:02,589 --> 00:02:04,889
to have been here this
morning, but unfortunately,

34
00:02:04,891 --> 00:02:08,791
we just can't fit any
more in, as you can tell.

35
00:02:08,795 --> 00:02:10,695
And so for the first time,

36
00:02:10,697 --> 00:02:13,467
we're not only live
streaming the Keynote,

37
00:02:13,467 --> 00:02:15,867
but we are live streaming
30 sessions

38
00:02:15,869 --> 00:02:18,439
of the conference as well.

39
00:02:18,438 --> 00:02:24,308
[Applause]

40
00:02:24,311 --> 00:02:27,651
Now, before we get right to
the show, I'd like to bring

41
00:02:27,647 --> 00:02:31,417
up something that I saw on
the news just a few days ago.

42
00:02:31,418 --> 00:02:33,718
This is Brandon Moss of
the Cleveland Indians,

43
00:02:33,720 --> 00:02:38,690
and he hit his 100th career
home run last Tuesday.

44
00:02:38,692 --> 00:02:40,832
Obviously, it's a huge milestone
if you are a baseball player.

45
00:02:40,827 --> 00:02:43,097
Not a lot of people do this.

46
00:02:43,096 --> 00:02:45,096
And you can imagine how much

47
00:02:45,098 --> 00:02:48,238
that ball would mean
to him to have it.

48
00:02:48,235 --> 00:02:52,605
It turns out the ball was hit
into the Indians' bull pen,

49
00:02:52,606 --> 00:02:57,046
and his teammates decided to
play a bit of a prank on him.

50
00:02:57,044 --> 00:03:01,014
They decided to hold
it for ransom.

51
00:03:01,014 --> 00:03:04,784
And this is the list of
things they asked for.

52
00:03:04,785 --> 00:03:10,295
[Laughter] Apple Watches,
iPads, MacBook Airs, iPhones.

53
00:03:10,290 --> 00:03:11,360
It's unbelievable.

54
00:03:11,358 --> 00:03:13,498
It's a shopping list
for the Apple Store.

55
00:03:13,493 --> 00:03:19,633
[Applause]

56
00:03:19,633 --> 00:03:22,603
Now, Brandon would have
had to raid an Apple Store

57
00:03:22,602 --> 00:03:24,202
to get that ball back.

58
00:03:24,204 --> 00:03:28,074
That didn't seem quite right
to us, and so what we're going

59
00:03:28,075 --> 00:03:31,345
to do is we're going
to pay the ransom.

60
00:03:31,344 --> 00:03:37,514
And I have the ball right here.

61
00:03:37,517 --> 00:03:45,527
[Applause]

62
00:03:45,525 --> 00:03:49,295
We are giving the ball to
Brandon, and we are going

63
00:03:49,296 --> 00:03:52,666
to give everything his
teammates asked for to them

64
00:03:52,666 --> 00:03:54,536
so everybody is happy.

65
00:03:54,534 --> 00:03:57,604
So congratulations, Brandon,
on a hundred home runs,

66
00:03:57,604 --> 00:03:59,544
and good luck on
the next hundred.

67
00:03:59,539 --> 00:04:04,779
[Applause]

68
00:04:04,778 --> 00:04:07,318
Now, we've got a
jam-packed morning for you.

69
00:04:07,314 --> 00:04:09,314
We are going to get
started with OS X.

70
00:04:09,316 --> 00:04:10,986
We are bringing a whole bunch

71
00:04:10,984 --> 00:04:14,284
of new great capabilities
to the Macintosh.

72
00:04:14,287 --> 00:04:18,087
And next we've got a
great update for iOS,

73
00:04:18,091 --> 00:04:21,491
the world's most advanced
mobile operating system.

74
00:04:21,495 --> 00:04:25,795
And today we're bringing
native apps

75
00:04:25,799 --> 00:04:28,569
to the Watch with a new version.

76
00:04:28,568 --> 00:04:33,208
[Applause]

77
00:04:33,206 --> 00:04:36,306
With a new version
of the watchOS,

78
00:04:36,309 --> 00:04:40,279
which gives the developers
even more time

79
00:04:40,280 --> 00:04:43,650
to create even greater
apps for the Watch

80
00:04:43,650 --> 00:04:45,920
that will change the world.

81
00:04:45,919 --> 00:04:49,589
Now, all three of these
ecosystems together provide

82
00:04:49,589 --> 00:04:53,029
incredible opportunities
for developers

83
00:04:53,026 --> 00:04:56,826
and unbelievable
possibilities for users.

84
00:04:56,830 --> 00:04:58,830
So we are very excited
about this.

85
00:04:58,832 --> 00:05:01,332
There's a lot here, and
so I am going to dispense

86
00:05:01,334 --> 00:05:03,504
with my normal updates other

87
00:05:03,503 --> 00:05:06,103
than to tell you
everything's going great.

88
00:05:06,106 --> 00:05:08,106
[Laughter]

89
00:05:08,108 --> 00:05:12,078
[Applause]

90
00:05:12,078 --> 00:05:13,578
And I'd like to bring
out my friend

91
00:05:13,580 --> 00:05:17,550
and colleague Craig Federighi to
take you through OS X and iOS.

92
00:05:17,551 --> 00:05:19,221
Craig.

93
00:05:20,620 --> 00:05:23,820
[Applause]

94
00:05:23,823 --> 00:05:25,163
CRAIG FEDERIGHI:
Good morning!

95
00:05:32,265 --> 00:05:34,165
It's fantastic to be
with you here at WWDC.

96
00:05:34,167 --> 00:05:37,267
The team has been doing
some amazing work this year,

97
00:05:37,270 --> 00:05:40,440
and I am thrilled to be able
to share it with you today.

98
00:05:40,440 --> 00:05:43,510
We are going to start with OS X.

99
00:05:43,510 --> 00:05:47,080
Now, our current release,
Yosemite, is a big, bold,

100
00:05:47,080 --> 00:05:50,650
beautiful release
with a gorgeous new UI

101
00:05:50,650 --> 00:05:53,820
and breakthrough features like
Continuity that let you work

102
00:05:53,820 --> 00:05:57,190
across your devices
like never before.

103
00:05:57,190 --> 00:06:01,260
Now, the adoption rate for
Yosemite is just incredible.

104
00:06:01,261 --> 00:06:04,001
In fact, over 55 percent

105
00:06:03,997 --> 00:06:06,797
of active Mac users are
running our latest update,

106
00:06:06,800 --> 00:06:11,240
and this is just unprecedented
in the history of our industry.

107
00:06:11,238 --> 00:06:15,908
[Laughter] In fact, Yosemite
has the fastest adoption rate

108
00:06:15,909 --> 00:06:18,249
for any PC operating
system ever.

109
00:06:18,245 --> 00:06:19,675
So thank you.

110
00:06:19,679 --> 00:06:26,149
[Applause]

111
00:06:26,152 --> 00:06:29,852
So for our next big release of
OS X, we knew we wanted to build

112
00:06:29,856 --> 00:06:32,156
on those strengths of Yosemite

113
00:06:32,158 --> 00:06:35,358
with some really great
refinements and advances.

114
00:06:35,362 --> 00:06:39,802
The only real question, of
course, was what to call it.

115
00:06:39,799 --> 00:06:45,639
So we had to once again turn to
our crack Apple Marketing Team.

116
00:06:45,639 --> 00:06:49,339
Now, in typical California
fashion, they started

117
00:06:49,342 --> 00:06:51,212
with a project kickoff meeting.

118
00:06:51,211 --> 00:06:53,011
[Laughter]

119
00:06:53,013 --> 00:06:56,483
And then headed immediately
into a team building off site.

120
00:06:56,483 --> 00:06:58,753
[Laughter]

121
00:06:58,752 --> 00:07:01,252
Now, of course they are in their
traditional Apple Marketing

122
00:07:01,254 --> 00:07:03,654
Free-Bottom Fridays attire.

123
00:07:03,657 --> 00:07:05,657
They say it's all
part of their process.

124
00:07:05,659 --> 00:07:07,759
I am not sure I get it.

125
00:07:07,761 --> 00:07:11,161
Ultimately, this
didn't yield any names,

126
00:07:11,164 --> 00:07:13,264
so they called in a consultant.

127
00:07:13,266 --> 00:07:15,266
[Laughter]

128
00:07:15,268 --> 00:07:19,638
He told them the answer
was to be found within.

129
00:07:19,639 --> 00:07:23,639
Not within themselves,
but within Yosemite.

130
00:07:23,643 --> 00:07:29,753
And so the new name for
OS X is OS X El Capitan.

131
00:07:29,749 --> 00:07:38,829
[Applause]

132
00:07:40,026 --> 00:07:41,766
For El Capitan, we focused
in two major areas --

133
00:07:41,761 --> 00:07:44,301
experience and performance.

134
00:07:44,297 --> 00:07:48,437
For experience, we've made
Spotlight more expressive,

135
00:07:48,435 --> 00:07:51,805
more powerful, and more
knowledgeable than ever.

136
00:07:51,805 --> 00:07:55,445
We've made big enhancements
to the apps you use most,

137
00:07:55,442 --> 00:07:58,482
and we made some real great
advancements in the area

138
00:07:58,478 --> 00:08:00,948
of how you manage
windows on the system.

139
00:08:00,947 --> 00:08:03,887
But rather than just talk about
it, I'd like to show it to you,

140
00:08:03,883 --> 00:08:06,783
so let's start with
a demo right now.

141
00:08:06,786 --> 00:08:11,426
[Applause]

142
00:08:11,424 --> 00:08:14,094
Now, your first task, of
course, in a demonstration

143
00:08:14,094 --> 00:08:17,094
or whenever you wake your
Mac, is finding the cursor,

144
00:08:17,097 --> 00:08:18,937
and El Capitan makes
this easier than ever.

145
00:08:18,932 --> 00:08:21,832
I just do that little
shake we all normally do,

146
00:08:21,835 --> 00:08:22,665
and there it is.

147
00:08:22,669 --> 00:08:23,599
It comes right out to greet you.

148
00:08:23,603 --> 00:08:24,803
It's really handy.

149
00:08:24,804 --> 00:08:28,974
[Applause]

150
00:08:28,975 --> 00:08:31,015
Now, we brought other great
gestures to the system.

151
00:08:31,010 --> 00:08:32,210
I am just going to
go here in Mail.

152
00:08:32,212 --> 00:08:34,412
I have a message here from Eddy.

153
00:08:34,414 --> 00:08:38,284
Looks like -- well, now --
[Laughter] -- that's a keeper.

154
00:08:38,284 --> 00:08:41,524
So I can actually mark
it unread to keep it just

155
00:08:41,521 --> 00:08:45,361
by swiping two fingers across
the trackpad just like that.

156
00:08:45,358 --> 00:08:48,428
And this one I'd kind of like
to delete, so I am just going

157
00:08:48,428 --> 00:08:50,098
to swipe it away just like that.

158
00:08:50,096 --> 00:08:52,136
So some real nice
little gestures.

159
00:08:52,132 --> 00:08:54,272
Let's move on now to Safari.

160
00:08:54,267 --> 00:08:57,307
Now, in Safari, I have some
sites that I like to keep

161
00:08:57,303 --> 00:09:00,073
around because I refer to them
on and off throughout the day,

162
00:09:00,073 --> 00:09:05,943
and now in Safari, I can pin
those sites just like this.

163
00:09:05,945 --> 00:09:08,985
So there's -- I am going to
pin my Twitter site here.

164
00:09:08,982 --> 00:09:11,282
And of course I have been
following the Warriors.

165
00:09:11,284 --> 00:09:13,354
Go Warriors, we are
going to get it done.

166
00:09:13,353 --> 00:09:15,353
[Applause]

167
00:09:15,355 --> 00:09:16,555
Just like that.

168
00:09:16,556 --> 00:09:19,096
Now, Pinned Sites have a
lot of special properties.

169
00:09:19,092 --> 00:09:22,562
For one, if I close this
window and reopen it,

170
00:09:22,562 --> 00:09:25,102
you see that my Pinned
Sites are all right there,

171
00:09:25,098 --> 00:09:26,998
and they load instantly.

172
00:09:26,999 --> 00:09:29,739
Now, Pinned Sites also behave
differently when I follow links,

173
00:09:29,736 --> 00:09:31,306
so I am just going
to click on one here,

174
00:09:31,304 --> 00:09:35,544
and you notice it opens in a new
tab, but my pinned site remains.

175
00:09:35,542 --> 00:09:37,912
Now I am going to open
up a couple more links.

176
00:09:37,911 --> 00:09:40,551
This one, let's see, this one.

177
00:09:40,547 --> 00:09:42,047
I will take a quick look.

178
00:09:42,048 --> 00:09:44,288
This one looks like some
kind of presentation video.

179
00:09:44,284 --> 00:09:45,514
This one is about the Giants.

180
00:09:45,518 --> 00:09:46,918
Have you ever had
this happen to you?

181
00:09:46,920 --> 00:09:50,260
You are like, Where is
this audio coming from?

182
00:09:50,256 --> 00:09:54,296
Now with just a tap,
you can mute it or find

183
00:09:54,294 --> 00:09:58,894
out where it came from and
shut it down just like that.

184
00:09:58,898 --> 00:10:03,768
[Applause]

185
00:10:03,770 --> 00:10:06,870
So I am interested in
seeing this Giants game,

186
00:10:06,873 --> 00:10:08,913
and now Spotlight can
actually help me out there.

187
00:10:08,908 --> 00:10:11,748
So I am just going to do a
search for the SF Giants,

188
00:10:11,744 --> 00:10:14,944
and we see right now I
get current game scores,

189
00:10:14,948 --> 00:10:16,248
upcoming games.

190
00:10:16,249 --> 00:10:18,519
Looks like the game I want
to go to is on Friday,

191
00:10:18,518 --> 00:10:21,958
so I can just search
for weather on Friday.

192
00:10:21,955 --> 00:10:23,285
See we get the weather.

193
00:10:23,289 --> 00:10:28,799
We can even resize the Spotlight
panel and move it around.

194
00:10:28,795 --> 00:10:32,895
I mean, there's innovation; huh?

195
00:10:32,899 --> 00:10:35,739
[Laughter] But I can also
express myself in my own words

196
00:10:35,735 --> 00:10:39,205
in Spotlight searches now, so
I can do things like slides

197
00:10:39,205 --> 00:10:41,275
from Brian, and you
see I find those there.

198
00:10:41,274 --> 00:10:45,274
But how about slides from
Brian about El Capitan?

199
00:10:45,278 --> 00:10:48,718
You see, I find exactly what I
am looking for in my own words.

200
00:10:48,715 --> 00:10:50,955
Now, this works great
in other apps as well.

201
00:10:50,950 --> 00:10:52,590
Let's try it out in Mail.

202
00:10:52,585 --> 00:10:55,425
So I've been really busy, of
course, the last couple of days,

203
00:10:55,421 --> 00:10:57,191
so I have been getting a
little behind on my Mail.

204
00:10:57,190 --> 00:11:00,390
I want to see the messages
that I've received from Phil

205
00:11:00,393 --> 00:11:01,833
but that I haven't
responded to yet.

206
00:11:01,828 --> 00:11:08,268
So I am just going to say
"mail I ignored from Phil."

207
00:11:09,569 --> 00:11:11,669
[Laughter] There are a few,
but I will be getting back

208
00:11:11,671 --> 00:11:15,111
to him right after the show.

209
00:11:15,108 --> 00:11:19,708
[Laughter] So next, of course,
it's great in the Finder

210
00:11:19,712 --> 00:11:23,052
as well, so if I wanted to look
at documents that I was working

211
00:11:23,049 --> 00:11:26,589
on last year at this time,
I might say something like

212
00:11:26,586 --> 00:11:31,856
"documents I worked
on last June."

213
00:11:31,858 --> 00:11:33,628
And I find exactly
what I am looking for.

214
00:11:33,626 --> 00:11:36,296
So this is really a
great way to search.

215
00:11:36,296 --> 00:11:38,796
Next I want to turn to window
management, so I am just going

216
00:11:38,798 --> 00:11:40,938
to run a script here that's
going to open up a whole bunch

217
00:11:40,934 --> 00:11:43,434
of windows to simulate kind
of what my desktop looks

218
00:11:43,436 --> 00:11:46,636
like after a day working on OS
X because it's a powerful system

219
00:11:46,639 --> 00:11:48,209
and we tend to have
a lot of things open.

220
00:11:48,207 --> 00:11:52,247
OS X provides some great ways
to navigate your windows,

221
00:11:52,245 --> 00:11:53,585
and one of those
is Mission Control.

222
00:11:53,580 --> 00:11:57,950
In El Capitan, we made
Mission Control smoother,

223
00:11:57,951 --> 00:11:59,481
simpler, and faster than ever.

224
00:11:59,485 --> 00:12:02,385
I am going to take three fingers
and swipe up on the trackpad.

225
00:12:02,388 --> 00:12:05,128
We get this gorgeous
overview of Mission Control.

226
00:12:05,124 --> 00:12:06,664
I'll just bring forward Safari.

227
00:12:06,659 --> 00:12:09,259
Let's do that again
and bring up Mail.

228
00:12:09,262 --> 00:12:10,062
Just like that.

229
00:12:10,063 --> 00:12:11,263
Works really great.

230
00:12:11,264 --> 00:12:13,404
Of course, OS X provides
great tools also

231
00:12:13,399 --> 00:12:15,769
to organize your windows, and
one of those is Full Screen.

232
00:12:15,768 --> 00:12:18,108
I am going to take this
window here full screen,

233
00:12:18,104 --> 00:12:20,044
and I am going to reply.

234
00:12:20,039 --> 00:12:22,779
Looks like there's a
message here from Eddy.

235
00:12:22,775 --> 00:12:26,375
He says sorry about bailing
on the team dinner last night.

236
00:12:26,379 --> 00:12:29,719
He was apparently
prepping for the Keynote.

237
00:12:29,716 --> 00:12:31,146
So that's understandable.

238
00:12:31,150 --> 00:12:35,220
But it looks like, actually,
I just got a new mail

239
00:12:35,221 --> 00:12:39,021
from Jeff here, and now I can
just click away, and it hides,

240
00:12:39,025 --> 00:12:41,895
and then -- oh, hold on.

241
00:12:41,894 --> 00:12:43,294
Busted, Eddy.

242
00:12:43,296 --> 00:12:45,336
So I think I'll just
drag this, actually,

243
00:12:45,331 --> 00:12:48,571
right into my Compose window,
it hops up automatically,

244
00:12:48,568 --> 00:12:49,698
and I can do it just like that.

245
00:12:49,702 --> 00:12:51,072
It's really great.

