296
00:15:04,403 --> 00:15:09,413
We saw gestures, for instance,
just swiping to delete in Mail.

297
00:15:09,408 --> 00:15:11,708
And, of course, pin
sites in Safari

298
00:15:11,711 --> 00:15:14,881
and the ability to
easily mute tabs.

299
00:15:14,881 --> 00:15:17,621
A great new Notes app that
supports text styling,

300
00:15:17,617 --> 00:15:20,717
checklists, and graphical links.

301
00:15:20,720 --> 00:15:22,690
And better window
management than ever

302
00:15:22,688 --> 00:15:26,758
with a beautiful new
Mission Control interface,

303
00:15:26,759 --> 00:15:29,959
easy access to your
spaces bar, and of course,

304
00:15:29,962 --> 00:15:33,662
the ability to do split
view and adjust it

305
00:15:33,666 --> 00:15:35,236
to see exactly what
you are looking for,

306
00:15:35,234 --> 00:15:38,374
every pixel of your display
devoted to your content.

307
00:15:38,371 --> 00:15:41,571
Of course, there's much more
to experience in El Capitan,

308
00:15:41,574 --> 00:15:45,374
but now I want to
turn to performance.

309
00:15:45,378 --> 00:15:49,618
So we've optimized performance
throughout the system.

310
00:15:49,615 --> 00:15:53,515
In fact, we are seeing about
a 1.4 times acceleration

311
00:15:53,519 --> 00:15:56,519
in app launching,
a 2x improvement

312
00:15:56,522 --> 00:15:59,292
in the snappiness
of switching apps.

313
00:15:59,292 --> 00:16:03,062
The time to get first Mail
messages, twice as fast.

314
00:16:03,062 --> 00:16:06,262
Opening a PDF in preview,
four times as fast.

315
00:16:06,265 --> 00:16:10,105
But we've also made deep
architectural improvements,

316
00:16:10,102 --> 00:16:13,272
and that brings us to Metal.

317
00:16:13,272 --> 00:16:16,172
[Applause]

318
00:16:16,175 --> 00:16:17,315
Thank you.

319
00:16:17,310 --> 00:16:20,050
Last year we introduced
Metal at WWDC as a way

320
00:16:20,046 --> 00:16:23,686
to accelerate graphics in
high-performance games.

321
00:16:23,683 --> 00:16:26,223
It takes the overhead
out of OpenGL,

322
00:16:26,219 --> 00:16:28,119
providing a high-performance API

323
00:16:28,120 --> 00:16:30,420
that gives the game
direct access to the power

324
00:16:30,423 --> 00:16:32,423
of the underlying
graphics hardware.

325
00:16:32,425 --> 00:16:36,025
Well, this year we are
bringing Metal to the Mac.

326
00:16:36,028 --> 00:16:38,398
And we are doing more than that.

327
00:16:38,397 --> 00:16:41,567
Because we are taking the
graphic stacks on which apps

328
00:16:41,567 --> 00:16:44,467
on OS X are built, Core
Animation and Core Graphics,

329
00:16:44,470 --> 00:16:48,910
and moving them from OpenGL to
run natively on top of Metal,

330
00:16:48,908 --> 00:16:50,808
making everything you do faster.

331
00:16:50,810 --> 00:16:53,150
We are seeing 50
percent improvements

332
00:16:53,145 --> 00:16:56,485
in rendering performance
and a 40 percent reduction

333
00:16:56,482 --> 00:16:59,122
in the amount of CPU
necessary to do graphics.

334
00:16:59,118 --> 00:17:01,658
That means improved performance
for your applications

335
00:17:01,654 --> 00:17:03,494
and better battery life.

336
00:17:03,489 --> 00:17:06,789
But the benefits of
Metal don't stop there.

337
00:17:06,792 --> 00:17:10,462
Metal's also great for
high-performance apps.

338
00:17:10,463 --> 00:17:14,503
In fact, Metal combines
the compute power of OpenCL

339
00:17:14,500 --> 00:17:15,970
and the graphics power of OpenGL

340
00:17:15,968 --> 00:17:21,008
in a higher performance
API that does both.

341
00:17:21,007 --> 00:17:22,337
And what we've seen from working

342
00:17:22,341 --> 00:17:26,081
with early pro developers
is really phenomenal.

343
00:17:26,078 --> 00:17:28,318
Adobe came in and,
in short order,

344
00:17:28,314 --> 00:17:31,684
was able to deliver an
eight times improvement

345
00:17:31,684 --> 00:17:35,054
in their rendering effects
inside of After Effects,

346
00:17:35,054 --> 00:17:37,994
and they have been able
to take the drawing engine

347
00:17:37,990 --> 00:17:41,590
in Illustrator, move it on top
of Metal, and take kinds of UI

348
00:17:41,594 --> 00:17:44,794
that previously was
noninteractive,

349
00:17:44,797 --> 00:17:47,697
like zoom of extremely
detailed drawings,

350
00:17:47,700 --> 00:17:49,670
and make it completely flawless

351
00:17:49,669 --> 00:17:52,269
and interactive,
thanks to Metal.

352
00:17:52,271 --> 00:17:54,711
Adobe is so pleased with this
they said they are committed

353
00:17:54,707 --> 00:17:57,247
to adopting Metal
on their OS X apps,

354
00:17:57,243 --> 00:17:59,613
seeing performance
increases up to 8x.

355
00:17:59,612 --> 00:18:01,582
They are excited
about what it can do

356
00:18:01,580 --> 00:18:03,750
for their Creative Cloud users.

357
00:18:03,749 --> 00:18:06,949
Of course, Metal is
also fantastic for games

358
00:18:06,953 --> 00:18:08,823
with a 10x improvement.

359
00:18:08,821 --> 00:18:13,691
That's ten times improvement
in drawing performance.

360
00:18:13,693 --> 00:18:17,563
So we brought in Epic to
see what they could do

361
00:18:17,563 --> 00:18:20,433
in short order, and the
results are really phenomenal.

362
00:18:20,433 --> 00:18:23,273
I'd like to welcome to
the stage Josh Adams

363
00:18:23,269 --> 00:18:26,309
and Billy Bramer
for a quick demo.

364
00:18:26,305 --> 00:18:28,675
[Applause]

365
00:18:28,674 --> 00:18:31,114
Thank you,
Craig.

366
00:18:31,110 --> 00:18:33,910
Thank you very much for
having us here today.

367
00:18:33,913 --> 00:18:37,683
So last year Metal
revolutionized graphics on iOS,

368
00:18:37,683 --> 00:18:42,293
and now Apple's amazed us again
by bringing Metal to the Mac.

369
00:18:42,288 --> 00:18:45,028
Of course, this is
great news for games,

370
00:18:45,024 --> 00:18:48,694
but also for the tools that
we use to make those games.

371
00:18:48,694 --> 00:18:51,864
Here you are seeing Epic's
upcoming multiplayer title

372
00:18:51,864 --> 00:18:54,064
Fortnite, running
entirely on Metal.

373
00:18:54,066 --> 00:18:57,236
We are modifying it directly
within the Unreal Engine,

374
00:18:57,236 --> 00:19:00,676
a development tool that powers
many of today's best games.

375
00:19:00,673 --> 00:19:02,543
It's quite a bit going
on in this scene, though,

376
00:19:02,541 --> 00:19:04,411
so let's break it down.

377
00:19:04,410 --> 00:19:07,010
First, there are
64 different layers

378
00:19:07,013 --> 00:19:10,613
of rendering effects,
and that's a lot.

379
00:19:10,616 --> 00:19:12,056
All combining together, though,

380
00:19:12,051 --> 00:19:14,491
to produce what you
see on the scene today.

381
00:19:14,487 --> 00:19:18,557
If we go into a simple wireframe
mode, you can see the thousands

382
00:19:18,557 --> 00:19:20,797
of building blocks that
make up this world.

383
00:19:20,793 --> 00:19:25,033
We can start to add in layers,
flat shading, detailed lighting,

384
00:19:25,031 --> 00:19:28,431
runtime shadows, and finally
we combine them all together

385
00:19:28,434 --> 00:19:31,104
to bring Fortnite's fun and
lighthearted aesthetic to life.

386
00:19:31,103 --> 00:19:33,503
The interesting thing
here, though,

387
00:19:33,506 --> 00:19:35,746
is that all of the effects
you are seeing are being done

388
00:19:35,741 --> 00:19:37,511
completely in real-time.

389
00:19:37,510 --> 00:19:39,810
Notice how the shadows and
objects interact nicely

390
00:19:39,812 --> 00:19:42,012
as Josh moves the car around.

391
00:19:42,014 --> 00:19:45,384
Finally, we can change the
time of day on the fly,

392
00:19:45,384 --> 00:19:48,684
dramatically altering the
mood of the entire scene.

393
00:19:48,687 --> 00:19:51,587
All of this is thanks to
the efficiency of Metal.

394
00:19:51,590 --> 00:19:54,760
In fact, we are seeing
a 70 percent reduction

395
00:19:54,760 --> 00:19:58,300
in CPUs compared to OpenGL,
enabling developers like us

396
00:19:58,297 --> 00:20:00,637
to create richer 3D worlds.

397
00:20:00,633 --> 00:20:05,333
Speaking of those worlds, let's
hop into the game, Fortnite.

398
00:20:05,337 --> 00:20:07,137
Now, if you've ever
built a pillow fort

399
00:20:07,139 --> 00:20:09,439
and battled imaginary
monsters with your friends,

400
00:20:09,442 --> 00:20:11,212
you already know how
to play Fortnite.

401
00:20:11,210 --> 00:20:13,250
This is the end-of-the-world
scenario you have been training

402
00:20:13,245 --> 00:20:15,285
for since you were a kid.

403
00:20:15,281 --> 00:20:17,751
It's a beautifully
stylized universe.

404
00:20:17,750 --> 00:20:20,050
You can destroy anything
you want.

405
00:20:20,052 --> 00:20:21,952
Gather resources
and build a fort.

406
00:20:21,954 --> 00:20:25,124
So let's go ahead
and wreck this car.

407
00:20:26,358 --> 00:20:28,258
Gather its metal.

408
00:20:28,260 --> 00:20:30,760
And continue our wanton
destruction by chopping

409
00:20:30,763 --> 00:20:32,563
down this tree to get
some wood for later.

410
00:20:32,565 --> 00:20:37,165
Did we mention there
are purple death storms,

411
00:20:37,169 --> 00:20:38,909
like this one, for instance?

412
00:20:38,904 --> 00:20:40,274
We should go.

413
00:20:40,272 --> 00:20:42,772
Luckily, while we were out
exploring, we found a multitude

414
00:20:42,775 --> 00:20:45,875
of weapons, and this broom.

415
00:20:45,878 --> 00:20:49,078
If we can just get
across the field,

416
00:20:49,081 --> 00:20:53,691
our friend has been busy
building a fort across the --

417
00:20:53,686 --> 00:20:55,386
did we mention the storms
are made of monsters?

418
00:20:55,387 --> 00:20:59,727
We are going to need something
a bit better than this broom.

419
00:20:59,725 --> 00:21:03,995
Nice! There's our friend
laying down some covering fire.

420
00:21:05,397 --> 00:21:07,737
Hey,
look out!

421
00:21:07,733 --> 00:21:11,303
We call that move
the power cord.

422
00:21:13,139 --> 00:21:14,509
I've got a bad feeling
about this.

423
00:21:14,507 --> 00:21:17,647
You are going to
need a bigger fort.

424
00:21:17,643 --> 00:21:20,243
Place a trap, head inside.

425
00:21:22,348 --> 00:21:24,148
Looks like an enemy has
broken into our fort.

426
00:21:24,150 --> 00:21:27,150
All right.

427
00:21:27,153 --> 00:21:30,293
Let's use that wood we gathered
earlier to fix this wall,

428
00:21:30,289 --> 00:21:34,589
build some stairs, meet up
with our friend topside.

429
00:21:36,228 --> 00:21:42,668
Glad you could
make it.

430
00:21:42,668 --> 00:21:44,808
[Monster screaming]

